      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "44e6eacd9da474c6",
      "text": "**Learning circles around the consequences of actions which impact an organization's operational work, how to learn from incidents and take action to avoid further problems of that type.**\n\n   Learning circles are structured forums or processes designed to facilitate reflection, knowledge sharing, and continuous improvement within an organization. These circles typically focus on analyzing the consequences of actions, such as incidents or operational disruptions, that impact the organization's work. By gathering relevant stakeholders, including those directly involved in the incident as well as subject matter experts, learning circles enable a comprehensive examination of what happened, why it happened, and how similar problems can be avoided in the future.\n\n   Through learning circles, organizations can identify root causes, systemic issues, and areas for improvement. They promote a culture of accountability, transparency, and collective learning, helping teams develop practical insights and actionable recommendations to mitigate future risks and enhance operational resilience. Additionally, implementing corrective measures and preventive controls based on the findings of learning circles strengthens the organization's ability to respond effectively to challenges and adapt to changing circumstances."
